<LP>
   CONSUMER PRICES ROSE 0.5% in March, pushing the
first-quarter inflation rate to 8.5%, the highest in eight
years. Though economists don't expect that pace to continue,
the figures suggest inflation remains a problem. There also
were signs of continued weakness in the economy.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Treasury bond prices slid following the inflation report,
pushing the yield on the benchmark 30-year issue to 8.72%,
the highest in almost a year. Stocks and the dollar were
mixed.
   ---
   Great American Bank said it needs to raise $350 million in
new capital by year-end because its auditor forced it to
boost loan-loss reserves. The disclosure raises questions
about the future of the nation's eighth-biggest S&amp;L.
   ---
   Employers were dealt a blow by the Supreme Court, which
upheld a federal labor policy that companies can't oust a
striking union by hiring new workers and asserting the
employees don't support the union.
   ---
   Citicorp and NCNB posted lower-than-expected quarterly
earnings as problem commercial loans ballooned.
                                                                                                       

   Three big California thrifts reported robust quarterly
profits, driven by a healthy housing market and widening net
interest margins.
   ---
   Ex-arbitrager Robert Freeman was given a four-month jail
term and ordered to pay $1 million in fines for his role in
an insider-trading case. He agreed in August to a guilty plea
and to resign from Goldman Sachs.
   ---
   Xoma sued rival Centocor for alleged patent infringement,
sparking the latest such fight in biotechnology.
   ---
   The NASD has proposed a long-awaited rule to tighten the
limits on fees charged by mutual funds. But the rule wouldn't
drastically change the way most funds charge investors.
   ---
   Amcor Capital faces more woes. The IRS proposed
disallowing some 1986 deductions by the agricultural
tax-shelter firm. Also, two men with ties to Amcor were
indicted.
   ---
   Deutsche Bank plans to form a venture with East Germany's
central bank, paving the way for the West German bank to take
a lead role in East Germany's finance industry.
   ---
   NCR's stock plunged $5.375, to $65.375, after the computer
maker posted a 15% drop in quarterly profit.
   ---
   Microsoft's profit soared 83% in its latest quarter as the
software maker continued to outperform competitors.
   ---
   Donaldson Lufkin was charged by the SEC with illegally
using customers' stock that was left in the care of the
firm's back-office operations. Donaldson settled the suit for
$5.6 million.
   ---
   General Electric posted a 12% increase in first-quarter
profit, citing strong gains at most major businesses, except
for the NBC unit.
   ---
   Norton's takeover defense against BTR of Britain is
expected to get some help from a new Massachusetts law. But
takeover speculators say the law may only delay a BTR
victory.
   ---
